Hm yeah this is a bit confusing. Right now this comes down to the following question for me, and before this is clear I think I cannot answer your questions properly. Let's say we have a custom model with these 'rules.
- road_class == MOTORWAY --> 100
- surface == GRAVEL --> 70
- road_environment == TUNNEL --> 80
For an edge that has all three attributes what do we expect:

100, because this is the first rule that matches (order matters)
80, because it is the last rule that matches (order matters). this sounds weird, but that would be the result if we had single if statements with no return (see below)
70, because out of all matches this is the most restrictive speed limit (I think this is done in master currently)
100, because we take the most restrictive speed limit but stop after the first match (sounds extra weird, but this is kind of what the last yaml with the if else looks like, see below)

In Java it would be this:
// 1
if (road_class == MOTORWAY)
   return 100;
if (surface == GRAVEL)
   return 70;
if (road_environment == TUNNEL)
   return 80;

// 2
double result;
if (road_class == MOTORWAY)
   result = 100;
if (surface == GRAVEL)
   result = 70;
if (road_environment == TUNNEL)
   result = 80;
return result;

// 3
double maxSpeed = encoder.maxSpeed();
if (road_class == MOTORWAY)
    maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
if (surface == GRAVEL)
    maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
if (road_environment == TUNNEL)
    maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);

// 4
double maxSpeed = encoder.maxSpeed();
if (road_class == MOTORWAY)
    maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
else if (surface == GRAVEL)
    maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
else if (road_environment == TUNNEL)
    maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
I guess the problem is that the logic we see in Java here gets 'lost' when converting this to yaml, or at least we have to be careful to make the yaml clear, but let's decide which Java logic we want first... And maybe we even need another option than the four I mentioned, e.g. combinations of these.
And note that I intentionally left out 'else' and 'maxSpeedFallback' here, because already without these its not clear to me at the moment.

So this
max_speed:
  - if: road_class == MOTORWAY
    then: 100
  - else if: surface == GRAVEL
    then: 70
  - else if: road_environment == TUNNEL
    then: 80
means:
double maxSpeed = encoder.getMaxSpeed();
if (road_class == MOTORWAY)
   maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
else if (surface == GRAVEL)
   maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 70);
else if (road_environment == TUNNEL)
   maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 80);
and this
max_speed:
  - if: road_class == MOTORWAY
    then: 100
  - if: surface == GRAVEL
    then: 70
  - if: road_environment == TUNNEL
    then: 80
means:
double maxSpeed = encoder.getMaxSpeed();
if (road_class == MOTORWAY)
   maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 100);
if (surface == GRAVEL)
   maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 70);
if (road_environment == TUNNEL)
   maxSpeed = Math.min(maxSpeed, 80);
?

